1
00:00:05,800 --> 00:00:07,320
(SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE)

2
00:00:09,040 --> 00:00:10,400
MAN: Who's that?

3
00:00:10,480 --> 00:00:12,640
(MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

4
00:00:22,920 --> 00:00:24,320
(LIFT BELL DINGING)

5
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:32,120
CLAIRE: Bed.
GEORGE: But Mum...

6
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:34,120
George, I won't tell you again,
get into bed.

7
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:35,280
(LIFT WHIRRING)

8
00:00:35,360 --> 00:00:37,760
I'm going to be late for work.
It's just the lift, love.

9
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:39,880
-How many more times?
-Don't like it.

10
00:00:39,960 --> 00:00:43,000
So, what do we do with the things
we don't like?

11
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:45,720
BOTH: Put them in the cupboard.

12
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:48,480
The thing.
You have to do the thing, Mum.

13
00:00:59,240 --> 00:01:01,920
Five times. It has to be five times.

14
00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:09,640
(WHISPERING)
Please save me from the monsters.

15
00:01:10,120 --> 00:01:12,200
Please save me from the monsters.

16
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:14,720
Please save me from the monsters.

17
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:17,040
You all right now?

18
00:01:17,640 --> 00:01:21,080
Come on, George,
there's nothing to be scared of.

19
00:01:23,200 --> 00:01:25,000
Goodnight, then, love.

20
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:34,400
ALEX: How is he?

21
00:01:35,080 --> 00:01:36,680
CLAIRE: He's in bed, at least.

22
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:49,640
I'm worried about him,
why is he terrified all the time?

23
00:01:49,720 --> 00:01:51,080
He needs help.

24
00:01:51,480 --> 00:01:54,200
-He's got us.
-He needs a doctor.

25
00:01:56,280 --> 00:01:58,440
GEORGE: (WHISPERING)
Please save me from the monsters.

26
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:00,880
Please save me from the monsters.

27
00:02:01,440 --> 00:02:03,400
Please save me from the monsters.

28
00:02:06,160 --> 00:02:08,240
"Please save me from the monsters."

29
00:02:10,160 --> 00:02:11,600
Haven't done this in a while.

30
00:02:11,680 --> 00:02:15,200
Um, done what? What are you doing?

31
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:18,960
Making a house call.

32
00:02:20,400 --> 00:02:22,720
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

33
00:02:55,520 --> 00:02:57,520
(WHOOSHING)

34
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:09,640
-No offence, Doctor...
-Meaning the opposite.

35
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:11,560
...but we could get a bus
somewhere like this.

36
00:03:11,640 --> 00:03:12,760
The exact opposite.

37
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:15,800
Well, I suppose it can't all be
planets and history and stuff, Rory.

38
00:03:15,880 --> 00:03:18,880
Yes, it can. Course it can.
Planets and history and stuff.

39
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:21,280
That's what we do. But not today, no.

40
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:26,440
Today we're answering a cry for help
from the scariest place in the universe.

41
00:03:26,520 --> 00:03:27,840
A child's bedroom.

42
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:29,360
(DOG BARKING)

43
00:03:30,480 --> 00:03:32,160
(WHEELS SQUEAKING)

44
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:40,080
(GEORGE PANTING)

45
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:42,680
(MUFFLED GROANING)

46
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:44,680
(WHEELS SQUEAKING OUTSIDE)

47
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
"Please save me from the monsters."
Who sent that?

48
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:09,160
That's what we're here to find out.

49
00:04:09,240 --> 00:04:10,560
Sounds like something a kid would say.

50
00:04:10,640 --> 00:04:13,600
Exactly. A scared kid.
A very scared kid.

51
00:04:14,240 --> 00:04:17,400
So scared that somehow his cry for help
got through to us in the Tardis.

52
00:04:17,480 --> 00:04:19,160
-Yeah, but you've traced it here.
-Exactly.

53
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:21,920
Ah, going up.

54
00:04:25,720 --> 00:04:29,240
WOMAN ON TV: Now, did you know
that there are twice as many pets

55
00:04:29,320 --> 00:04:32,160
as people here in the UK?
Now, that's a lot of animals.

56
00:04:32,240 --> 00:04:34,800
And we want to know how clever they are.

57
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:36,960
Now, if you were watching BBC One
on Saturday night,

58
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:38,840
you will have seen Rolf Harris
and Kate Humble...

59
00:04:38,920 --> 00:04:40,720
(GASPING)

60
00:04:57,160 --> 00:04:58,200
Hi.

61
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Hello.

62
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:06,560
Are your mummy and daddy in
or is it just you?

63
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:09,720
Okay.

64
00:05:09,800 --> 00:05:11,720
-Is it about the bins?
-Pardon?

65
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:17,720
Community Support, just checking up
on community...based...things.

66
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:18,960
-Can I help you?
-Hi.

67
00:05:19,040 --> 00:05:21,400
Um, yeah, no, sorry, I was just
wondering if you've had any bother

68
00:05:21,480 --> 00:05:23,120
-around here?
-Is everything okay?

69
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:24,320
The bins!

70
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:27,880
I can't be expected to get down
all them stairs, I need new knees.

71
00:05:27,960 --> 00:05:30,040
-Bother? What do you mean?
-Well, I mean...

72
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:32,240
Are your neighbours nice?
You get on well?

73
00:05:32,320 --> 00:05:34,000
-He didn't send you, did he?
-Who?

74
00:05:34,080 --> 00:05:36,880
Jim Purcell. Course we get on well.
I'm their landlord.

75
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:38,120
They love me, don't they?

76
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:39,240
You're the landlord?

77
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:42,120
-Not the bins, no, Miss...
-Mrs Rossiter.

78
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:44,520
I thought you'd know that,
being from Community Support.

79
00:05:44,600 --> 00:05:47,640
Yeah. Yes, no, yes, of course.

80
00:05:47,720 --> 00:05:50,600
I've already got a new hip, I'll be able
to manage when I get the knees.

81
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:53,680
Up, down them stairs like
Sherpa Tenzing then.

82
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:55,480
-Can I come in?
-Oh.

83
00:05:58,320 --> 00:06:01,240
-Course not. You could be anyone.
-I could be, but I'm not.

84
00:06:01,320 --> 00:06:03,560
Or maybe it's best
if I come back another time.

85
00:06:03,640 --> 00:06:04,640
I'm the Doctor.

86
00:06:14,080 --> 00:06:16,040
(GEORGE BREATHING RAPIDLY)

87
00:06:20,640 --> 00:06:21,840
(METAL CLANGING)

88
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:23,360
(WOMAN LAUGHING)

89
00:06:35,960 --> 00:06:37,160
We've got to find that kid.

90
00:06:37,240 --> 00:06:40,480
Maybe we should let the monsters
gobble him up.

91
00:07:01,800 --> 00:07:03,160
Hey, any luck?

92
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:06,120
Three old ladies, a traffic warden
from Croatia and a man with 10 cats.

93
00:07:06,200 --> 00:07:09,040
-What are we actually looking for?
-10 cats! Scared kid, remember?

94
00:07:09,120 --> 00:07:11,080
I found, um, scary kids.
Is that kinda...

95
00:07:11,160 --> 00:07:13,480
Hmm, try the next floor down.
Catch you later.

96
00:07:14,160 --> 00:07:15,360
Okay.

97
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:17,840
Maybe it was, you know, junk mail.

98
00:07:17,920 --> 00:07:19,200
-What?
-(LIFT BELL DINGS)

99
00:07:19,280 --> 00:07:22,280
The message on the psychic paper,
maybe it was just nothing.

100
00:07:37,280 --> 00:07:39,000
(SCREAMING)

101
00:07:50,440 --> 00:07:52,000
(DINGS)

102
00:08:04,600 --> 00:08:07,040
Oh, right, that was quick, was it?

103
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:09,040
Claire said she'd phoned someone.

104
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:11,560
-Social Services.
-Yes. Yes.

105
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:13,720
It's not easy, you know.

106
00:08:15,080 --> 00:08:16,160
Admitting your kid's got a problem.

107
00:08:16,240 --> 00:08:17,640
You've got a problem,
I've got a problem.

108
00:08:17,720 --> 00:08:18,920
I'm better connected, I'm the Doctor.

109
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:20,720
Call me Doctor. Uh, what can I call you?

110
00:08:21,240 --> 00:08:22,720
-Um, Alex.
-Hello, Alex.

111
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:24,920
So,

112
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:28,640
tell me about George.

113
00:08:40,320 --> 00:08:42,040
A blooming mess.

114
00:08:44,400 --> 00:08:48,040
I'm the only one who gives
a monkey's around here any more.

115
00:08:50,360 --> 00:08:51,760
Shocking.

116
00:08:53,280 --> 00:08:56,600
(CHUCKLES)
Talking to yourself now, Elsie.

117
00:08:57,400 --> 00:08:59,080
They say it's the first sign.

118
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:04,560
Oh, Lord.

119
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:09,000
Come out of there!

120
00:09:11,040 --> 00:09:12,360
Don't be so ruddy horrible.

121
00:09:12,440 --> 00:09:14,600
Trying to scare an old lady to death.

122
00:09:17,120 --> 00:09:18,360
It's not right.

123
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:21,760
Is that you, George?

124
00:09:23,800 --> 00:09:25,520
I'll tell your Mum and Dad.

125
00:09:30,240 --> 00:09:32,960
Come on, you little devil.
Let's see your face.

126
00:09:34,800 --> 00:09:36,680
(MRS ROSSITER SCREAMING)

127
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,120
Ever since he was born,
he's been a funny kid.

128
00:09:46,200 --> 00:09:48,040
Funny's good, we like funny, don't we?

129
00:09:48,920 --> 00:09:50,120
ALEX: Well, he never cries.

130
00:09:50,880 --> 00:09:52,640
Bottles it all up, I suppose.

131
00:09:53,680 --> 00:09:55,280
Tell him off, he just looks at you.

132
00:09:55,640 --> 00:09:57,600
-How old is he?
-He was eight in January.

133
00:09:58,160 --> 00:10:01,840
I mean, he should be growing out
of stuff like this, shouldn't he?

134
00:10:01,920 --> 00:10:03,080
Maybe.

135
00:10:04,920 --> 00:10:06,680
It's got worse, though, lately?

136
00:10:06,760 --> 00:10:09,080
Yeah, we talked about getting help.

137
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:11,120
You know, maybe sending him somewhere.

138
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:14,200
He started getting these
nervous ticks, you know?

139
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:16,200
Funny little cough,
blinking all the time.

140
00:10:16,280 --> 00:10:18,320
But now it's got completely out of hand.

141
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:19,920
I mean, he's scared to death
of everything.

142
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:21,080
-Pantophobia.
-What?

143
00:10:21,160 --> 00:10:22,440
That's what it's called, pantophobia.

144
00:10:22,520 --> 00:10:24,400
Not a fear of pants, though,
if that's what you're thinking.

145
00:10:24,480 --> 00:10:27,760
It's a fear of everything.
Including pants, I suppose.

146
00:10:27,840 --> 00:10:30,000
In that case, sorry, go on.

147
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:32,880
-He hates crayons...
-Understandable.

148
00:10:32,960 --> 00:10:35,720
Old toys. He thinks the old lady
across the way is a witch.

149
00:10:35,800 --> 00:10:38,280
He hates having a bath, in case
there is something under the water.

150
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:40,680
The lift sounds
like someone breathing, it's...

151
00:10:42,120 --> 00:10:44,040
(SIGHS) Look, I don't know.

152
00:10:46,440 --> 00:10:48,120
I'm not an expert.

153
00:10:50,040 --> 00:10:53,440
-Maybe you can get through to him.
-I'll do my best.

154
00:10:56,760 --> 00:10:59,120
-Amy?
-Hmm?

155
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:02,000
-(WHISPERS) Amy! Are you here?
-Here.

156
00:11:02,920 --> 00:11:04,200
Here! Ow!

157
00:11:04,280 --> 00:11:05,920
I'm here, it's me.

158
00:11:08,840 --> 00:11:11,000
-You okay?
-Yeah, I think so.

159
00:11:11,440 --> 00:11:15,040
What happened to the lift?
We were in a lift, right?

160
00:11:15,120 --> 00:11:17,320
Yeah, yeah, we were...
I remember getting in and then...

161
00:11:17,400 --> 00:11:18,920
-(GROANS)
- What?

162
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:20,760
-We're dead, aren't we?
-Hey?

163
00:11:20,840 --> 00:11:22,160
-The lift fell and we're dead.
-Shut up.

164
00:11:22,240 --> 00:11:24,840
-We're dead. Again.
-Oh, shut up.

165
00:11:24,920 --> 00:11:26,240
Let's just find out where we are.

166
00:11:41,280 --> 00:11:43,040
-You know, it's obvious what's happened.
-Yeah?

167
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:45,080
Really? Because it's not obvious to me.

168
00:11:45,160 --> 00:11:46,800
The Tardis has gone funny again.

169
00:11:46,880 --> 00:11:50,440
Some time...slippy...thing.

170
00:11:50,520 --> 00:11:52,600
You know, the Doctor is back there
in EastEnders-land

171
00:11:52,680 --> 00:11:54,680
and we're stuck here in the past.

172
00:11:54,760 --> 00:11:58,720
-This is probably 1700 and something.
-Yay. My favourite year.

173
00:12:10,120 --> 00:12:11,400
(LIFT DINGS)

174
00:12:11,480 --> 00:12:13,600
(WHIRRING)

175
00:12:13,680 --> 00:12:15,360
(GLASS SHATTERING)

176
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,160
George, you okay? What's the matter?

177
00:12:20,040 --> 00:12:21,040
Oh.

178
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:25,160
Never mind.

179
00:12:28,040 --> 00:12:29,360
Were you having a nightmare, son?

180
00:12:29,440 --> 00:12:31,960
It wasn't a nightmare. I wasn't asleep.

181
00:12:34,520 --> 00:12:37,000
-Who are you?
-I'm the Doctor.

182
00:12:37,080 --> 00:12:39,760
A doctor? Have you come
to take me away?

183
00:12:39,840 --> 00:12:42,000
No, George. I just want to talk to you.

184
00:12:42,080 --> 00:12:43,240
What about?

185
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:50,480
About the monsters.

186
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:08,440
(UTENSILS FALLING)

187
00:13:10,680 --> 00:13:11,960
Bit neglected, wherever it is.

188
00:13:12,040 --> 00:13:15,240
Let's find the front door, at least.
We can work out where we are.

189
00:13:15,320 --> 00:13:16,640
When we are.

190
00:13:17,240 --> 00:13:18,320
(KNOCKING)

191
00:13:18,400 --> 00:13:19,840
-Rory.
-Hmm?

192
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:21,360
Look at this.

193
00:13:22,440 --> 00:13:26,200
-Well, it's a copper pan.
-No, it's not. It's wood.

194
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:28,640
It's made of wood and just
painted to look like copper.

195
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:30,200
That is stupid.

196
00:13:34,280 --> 00:13:35,760
Rory, hang on.

197
00:13:40,400 --> 00:13:41,760
There's a switch.

198
00:13:44,520 --> 00:13:48,280
Wow, well, not 1700 and something, then.

199
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:03,960
(BOTH SCREAM)

200
00:14:13,760 --> 00:14:14,880
(SQUEAKING)

201
00:14:17,360 --> 00:14:19,920
It's glass. It's a glass eye.

202
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:28,640
-Stop doing that.
-It's not me.

203
00:14:34,040 --> 00:14:35,160
-Come on.
-Yeah.

204
00:14:38,440 --> 00:14:39,520
Hang on.

205
00:14:47,880 --> 00:14:49,720
ALEX: Maybe it was things on telly.

206
00:14:49,800 --> 00:14:51,160
-You know?
-Right.

207
00:14:51,240 --> 00:14:54,200
Scary stuff. Getting under his skin.

208
00:14:54,280 --> 00:14:55,800
-Frightening him.
-Uh-huh.

209
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:58,680
-So we stopped letting him watch.
-Oh, you don't want to do that.

210
00:14:59,800 --> 00:15:02,120
And Claire thought it might be
something he was reading.

211
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:04,600
Great. Reading is great.
Do you like stories, George?

212
00:15:06,160 --> 00:15:07,240
Yeah? Me, too.

213
00:15:07,320 --> 00:15:10,800
When I was your age,
about, oh, a thousand years ago,

214
00:15:10,880 --> 00:15:12,400
I loved a good bedtime story.

215
00:15:12,480 --> 00:15:15,360
The Three Little Sontarans,
The Emperor Dalek's New Clothes,

216
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:17,320
Snow White and the Seven Keys
to Doomsday, eh?

217
00:15:17,400 --> 00:15:18,440
All the classics.

218
00:15:18,520 --> 00:15:20,600
Rubbish, must be broken.
Hate those things.

219
00:15:22,240 --> 00:15:23,960
Better tidy it away, though, eh?

220
00:15:26,840 --> 00:15:27,840
How about in here?

221
00:15:28,280 --> 00:15:29,440
(GASPS)

222
00:15:31,280 --> 00:15:33,760
No, not in the cupboard.
Why not in there, George?

223
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:35,840
It's a...thing.

224
00:15:36,480 --> 00:15:38,160
Thing we got him doing ages back.

225
00:15:38,240 --> 00:15:40,640
Anything that frightens him,
we put it in the cupboard.

226
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:43,400
Creepy toys, scary pictures,
that sort of thing.

227
00:15:43,480 --> 00:15:44,800
And is that where the monsters go?

228
00:15:46,360 --> 00:15:47,720
Yeah.

229
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:54,400
There's nothing to be scared of, George.

230
00:15:56,320 --> 00:15:57,560
It's just a cupboard.

231
00:16:06,080 --> 00:16:07,400
(LOUD KNOCKING ON THE DOOR)

232
00:16:08,400 --> 00:16:09,520
(SIGHING)

233
00:16:09,600 --> 00:16:10,920
Front door.

234
00:16:27,480 --> 00:16:29,240
(WHISPERING) Let's try down here.

235
00:16:37,160 --> 00:16:40,000
-Evening.
-Oh, hi.

236
00:16:40,520 --> 00:16:43,600
-PURCELL: How's Claire?
-Good, thanks, at work.

237
00:16:43,680 --> 00:16:46,440
Look, um, this really isn't a good time.
Maybe later...

238
00:16:46,520 --> 00:16:48,040
And the kiddie?

239
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:51,040
Good.

240
00:16:51,560 --> 00:16:54,480
You know I hate to mention it,
but it's that time again.

241
00:16:54,600 --> 00:16:58,080
-Yes.
-And you know I like my money prompt.

242
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:04,480
ALEX: The thing is, I still haven't
found anywhere since the shop shut

243
00:17:04,560 --> 00:17:06,160
and Claire's wage only goes so far.

244
00:17:06,240 --> 00:17:08,760
I thought you could, you know,
come up with some sort of arrangement.

245
00:17:08,840 --> 00:17:11,360
-Is that a torch?
-Screwdriver.

246
00:17:11,440 --> 00:17:13,960
PURCELL: No can do, son.
I mean, if I went around...

247
00:17:14,040 --> 00:17:15,160
A sonic one.

248
00:17:15,240 --> 00:17:16,800
(HIGH FREQUENCY BEEPING)
And other stuff.

249
00:17:18,040 --> 00:17:20,600
-Please, may I see the other stuff?
-You may.

250
00:17:24,360 --> 00:17:26,080
Huh? Pretty cool, eh?

251
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:41,280
(GROWLING)

252
00:17:41,360 --> 00:17:43,360
Listen to him. Isn't he awful, eh?

253
00:17:43,440 --> 00:17:46,080
Don't growl at the nice man, Bernard.

254
00:17:47,040 --> 00:17:49,040
He doesn't mean to upset Daddy.

255
00:17:49,120 --> 00:17:50,800
-Do you?
-No.

256
00:17:52,640 --> 00:17:54,040
Look, son.

257
00:17:54,120 --> 00:17:55,240
I know what you're thinking.

258
00:17:55,320 --> 00:17:59,920
Here comes horrible Purcell,
after his rent, dog on a chain.

259
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,720
(EXCLAIMS) See?
Weren't expecting that, was ya?

260
00:18:04,320 --> 00:18:05,760
(SIGHS)

261
00:18:05,840 --> 00:18:08,120
I'm not as daft as I look.

262
00:18:08,200 --> 00:18:10,400
In fact, I'm not daft at all.

263
00:18:16,880 --> 00:18:18,760
Huh? That's better.

264
00:18:18,840 --> 00:18:21,840
No tears from George,
that's what I've heard.

265
00:18:21,920 --> 00:18:24,760
Go on, give us a smile.
There's a brave little soldier.

266
00:18:26,680 --> 00:18:28,560
Bit rusty at this. Anyway...

267
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:32,280
Let's open this cupboard, eh?
Now there's nothing to be...

268
00:18:32,360 --> 00:18:34,240
(BEEPING RAPIDLY)

269
00:18:34,600 --> 00:18:37,440
(WHISPERING)
Off the scale. Off the scale.

270
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:40,640
Off the scale.

271
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:46,160
PURCELL: ALLI want is my £350.

272
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:48,720
Simple as that.

273
00:18:49,520 --> 00:18:50,640
(BERNARD GROWLING)

274
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:52,120
Goodnight.

275
00:18:52,920 --> 00:18:54,440
Come on, son, come on.

276
00:18:59,800 --> 00:19:02,200
Right, sorry about that.

277
00:19:04,640 --> 00:19:07,160
-So, have you got this thing open yet?
-No! No, no, no, no, no.

278
00:19:08,160 --> 00:19:09,560
-You don't want to do that.
-Why?

279
00:19:11,040 --> 00:19:13,240
Because George's monsters are real.

280
00:19:23,840 --> 00:19:25,240
Oh, at last.

281
00:19:26,880 --> 00:19:28,720
- (EXCLAIMS)
-What is it?

282
00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:30,880
No door knob.

283
00:19:30,960 --> 00:19:34,440
Wooden pans, a massive glass eye
and now no door knob!

284
00:19:34,520 --> 00:19:35,800
And this clock.

285
00:19:36,640 --> 00:19:39,120
-What?
-Look, the hands. They're painted on.

286
00:19:40,960 --> 00:19:42,760
(CHILD LAUGHING)

287
00:19:53,400 --> 00:19:54,720
You're supposed to be a professional.

288
00:19:55,280 --> 00:19:57,720
I'll never get him to sleep now.
You're so...

289
00:19:57,800 --> 00:20:00,040
-Irresponsible.
-No, Alex. Responsible. Very.

290
00:20:00,120 --> 00:20:02,480
Cupboard bad. Cupboard not bare.
Stay away from cupboard.

291
00:20:02,560 --> 00:20:04,440
And there's something else.
Something I've missed. Something...

292
00:20:04,520 --> 00:20:05,680
staring me in the face.

293
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:08,000
Look, I'd like you to leave, please.
You're just making things worse.

294
00:20:09,040 --> 00:20:12,000
Will you stop making tea?
I want you to leave!

295
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:14,440
-No.
-What?

296
00:20:14,520 --> 00:20:16,320
What do you mean, no?

297
00:20:17,320 --> 00:20:18,840
Leave. Get out.

298
00:20:20,280 --> 00:20:21,680
Now, please.

299
00:20:24,680 --> 00:20:28,120
Look, maybe this was a bad idea.
We should sort out George ourselves.

300
00:20:28,200 --> 00:20:29,280
You can't.

301
00:20:30,680 --> 00:20:33,000
No one's going to tell us
how to run our lives.

302
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:36,760
I don't care who you are or what wheels
have been set in motion, we'll sort it.

303
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:40,480
I'm not just a professional,
I'm the Doctor.

304
00:20:40,560 --> 00:20:41,600
What's that supposed to mean?

305
00:20:41,680 --> 00:20:44,360
It means I've come a long way
to get here, Alex, a very long way.

306
00:20:44,440 --> 00:20:46,800
George sent a message.
A distress call, if you like.

307
00:20:46,880 --> 00:20:50,320
Whatever's inside that cupboard
is so terrible, so powerful,

308
00:20:50,400 --> 00:20:52,760
that it amplified the fears
of an ordinary little boy

309
00:20:52,840 --> 00:20:54,400
across all the barriers
of time and space.

310
00:20:54,480 --> 00:20:57,320
-Eh?
-Through crimson stars and silent stars

311
00:20:57,400 --> 00:21:01,040
and tumbling nebulas
like oceans set on fire,

312
00:21:01,120 --> 00:21:04,280
through empires of glass
and civilizations of pure thought

313
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:07,560
and a whole, terrible, wonderful
universe of impossibilities.

314
00:21:07,640 --> 00:21:10,600
You see, these eyes, they're all lies.

315
00:21:11,880 --> 00:21:13,840
And one thing I can tell you, Alex.

316
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:17,720
Monsters are real.

317
00:21:20,760 --> 00:21:22,760
You're not from Social Services,
are you?

318
00:21:25,480 --> 00:21:28,360
First things first.
You got any Jammie Dodgers?

319
00:21:28,440 --> 00:21:31,440
MRS ROSSITER: Please.
I don't like being on me own.

320
00:21:33,120 --> 00:21:35,000
Is there anyone here?

321
00:21:36,480 --> 00:21:37,840
Please.

322
00:21:38,960 --> 00:21:40,480
Help me.

323
00:21:45,240 --> 00:21:46,840
(CHILD LAUGHING)

324
00:22:01,200 --> 00:22:02,240
(CHILD LAUGHING)

325
00:22:03,800 --> 00:22:05,520
-You hear that?
-Yeah.

326
00:22:05,600 --> 00:22:07,320
(CHILD CONTINUES LAUGHING)

327
00:22:08,800 --> 00:22:09,960
Wait.

328
00:22:10,880 --> 00:22:13,080
(LAUGHING GETS LOUDER)

329
00:22:15,600 --> 00:22:17,040
AMY: They're getting closer.

330
00:22:17,840 --> 00:22:19,240
"They"?

331
00:22:22,440 --> 00:22:24,040
(CHILD LAUGHING)

332
00:22:56,760 --> 00:22:58,480
(BOTH SCREAMING)

333
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:03,800
Oh, it's just a... It's a dummy.
Oh, it's just a dummy.

334
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:06,600
This is weird.

335
00:23:06,680 --> 00:23:08,880
Yes, says the time-travelling nurse.

336
00:23:13,800 --> 00:23:16,360
Yeah, um, let's just leave that for now,
come on.

337
00:23:20,400 --> 00:23:24,160
CHILDREN: # Tick-tock goes the clock

338
00:23:24,240 --> 00:23:27,760
-(CREAKING, GIGGLING)
-# And others shall be born... #

339
00:23:29,920 --> 00:23:31,360
(LIFT DINGING)

340
00:23:31,440 --> 00:23:33,000
DOCTOR: What is it with these photos?

341
00:23:33,280 --> 00:23:36,200
Anyway, good, nice tea.
Nothing like a cuppa but...

342
00:23:36,320 --> 00:23:38,480
Decision, should we open the cupboard?

343
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:41,680
-What? Well...
-Should we?

344
00:23:41,760 --> 00:23:43,160
Got to open the cupboard, haven't we?
Course we have.

345
00:23:43,240 --> 00:23:44,360
Come on, Alex, Alex, come on,

346
00:23:44,440 --> 00:23:46,320
how else will we ever find out
what's going on here?

347
00:23:46,400 --> 00:23:48,360
-Right, but you said...
-Monsters, yeah, well, that's what I do,

348
00:23:48,440 --> 00:23:51,200
breakfast, dinner and tea.
Fight the monsters, so this,

349
00:23:51,280 --> 00:23:53,840
this is just an average day
at the office for me.

350
00:23:53,920 --> 00:23:54,920
Okay, yeah, you're right.

351
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:56,000
Or maybe we shouldn't
open the cupboard.

352
00:23:56,120 --> 00:23:57,440
-Eh?
-We have no idea what might be in there.

353
00:23:57,520 --> 00:23:59,360
How powerful,
how evil that thing might be.

354
00:23:59,440 --> 00:24:00,880
-We don't?
-Come on, Alex, Alex, come on.

355
00:24:00,960 --> 00:24:02,840
Are you crazy?
We can't open the cupboard.

356
00:24:02,920 --> 00:24:05,560
-God, no! No, we mustn't.
-Right.

357
00:24:05,640 --> 00:24:07,720
-That settles it.
-Settles what?

358
00:24:10,960 --> 00:24:12,560
Going to open the cupboard.

359
00:24:14,120 --> 00:24:16,320
PURCELL: There's nothing on.

360
00:24:16,400 --> 00:24:18,920
Never anything on, is there, Bernard?

361
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,960
Bergerac, God help us.
30 years old, that.

362
00:24:22,440 --> 00:24:23,560
(GROWLING)

363
00:24:23,640 --> 00:24:25,600
Where's the boxing?
There's meant to be boxing on.

364
00:24:30,560 --> 00:24:32,960
Looks we're going to have to watch
that film again.

365
00:24:39,240 --> 00:24:40,920
(CREAKING)

366
00:24:41,760 --> 00:24:44,160
What the... Hold on a minute.

367
00:24:45,520 --> 00:24:46,640
(GRUNTS)

368
00:24:48,560 --> 00:24:49,880
This is not...

369
00:24:53,600 --> 00:24:54,720
(SCREAMS)

370
00:24:55,840 --> 00:24:57,400
Help me, Bernard. Oh!

371
00:24:59,400 --> 00:25:00,560
Ah!

372
00:25:02,080 --> 00:25:03,640
(GROWLS)

373
00:25:07,400 --> 00:25:09,040
(CRACKS)

374
00:25:16,320 --> 00:25:19,560
(GEORGE BREATHING HEAVILY)

375
00:25:24,680 --> 00:25:25,840
Oh!

376
00:25:37,680 --> 00:25:39,400
(BREATHING GETS HEAVIER)

377
00:25:40,400 --> 00:25:42,280
(GASPS)

378
00:25:51,480 --> 00:25:53,280
I don't understand.
It has to be the cupboard.

379
00:25:53,360 --> 00:25:55,800
The readings from the sonic screwdriver,
they were...

380
00:25:56,560 --> 00:25:57,840
You...

381
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:08,080
-How old is George, Alex?
-What? How old?

382
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:10,480
-Yes. How old is George?
-Well, I told you, he just turned eight.

383
00:26:10,560 --> 00:26:12,360
-So you remember when he was born, then?
-Of course.

384
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:13,640
Of course you do. How could you not?

385
00:26:13,720 --> 00:26:15,800
You and Claire, Christmas Eve,
2002, right?

386
00:26:15,880 --> 00:26:16,960
What? Oh, yeah.

387
00:26:17,040 --> 00:26:18,040
A couple of weeks
before George was born.

388
00:26:18,120 --> 00:26:19,760
Tell me about the day he arrived,
must have been wonderful.

389
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:21,640
Well, it was the best day of my...

390
00:26:24,080 --> 00:26:25,520
-life.
-Sure?

391
00:26:27,080 --> 00:26:28,760
-Yes.
-You don't sound sure.

392
00:26:30,160 --> 00:26:31,640
What are you trying to say?

393
00:26:32,720 --> 00:26:35,800
Look, I don't like this.
I told you before, I want you to go.

394
00:26:35,880 --> 00:26:37,880
-What's the matter, Alex?
-I can't...

395
00:26:38,960 --> 00:26:40,240
Oh, no.

396
00:26:40,960 --> 00:26:43,600
-Oh, this is scary.
-No, Alex, this is scary.

397
00:26:43,680 --> 00:26:45,440
Claire with baby George, newborn, yes?

398
00:26:45,520 --> 00:26:47,240
-Yes.
-Less than a month after Christmas.

399
00:26:47,320 --> 00:26:49,320
-So0?
-So, look, look. Claire's not pregnant.

400
00:26:49,400 --> 00:26:50,400
-What?
-Not pregnant.

401
00:26:50,480 --> 00:26:52,640
Well, of course not.
Claire can't have kids!

402
00:26:56,440 --> 00:26:58,680
-Say that again?
-We tried everything.

403
00:26:59,320 --> 00:27:02,120
She was desperate.
As much IVF as we could afford but...

404
00:27:05,880 --> 00:27:07,400
Claire can't have kids.

405
00:27:14,080 --> 00:27:15,360
How...

406
00:27:16,080 --> 00:27:17,720
How can I have forgotten that?

407
00:27:27,520 --> 00:27:28,920
Who are you, George?

408
00:27:31,840 --> 00:27:34,000
It's not possible. This isn't...

409
00:27:36,520 --> 00:27:37,680
-George?
-(LIFT BELL DINGS)

410
00:27:37,760 --> 00:27:39,480
(LIFT WHIRRING)

411
00:27:52,560 --> 00:27:53,560
(GASPS)

412
00:27:54,680 --> 00:27:56,120
DOCTOR: George!

413
00:27:58,240 --> 00:28:00,400
George, what's going on?
Are you doing this?

414
00:28:00,480 --> 00:28:01,560
What's happening?

415
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:05,320
Please save me from the monsters.
Please save me from the monsters.

416
00:28:05,400 --> 00:28:07,280
-ALEX: George!
-Please save me from the monsters.

417
00:28:07,360 --> 00:28:09,480
Please save me from the monsters.

418
00:28:09,560 --> 00:28:11,280
-ALEX: George! Ah!
-Please save me from the monsters.

419
00:28:11,360 --> 00:28:13,520
Please save me from the monsters.

420
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:15,440
Please save me from the monsters.

421
00:28:15,520 --> 00:28:17,080
(ALEX SCREAMING)

422
00:28:17,720 --> 00:28:19,880
-DOCTOR: George! Help!
-(ALEX SCREAMING)

423
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:21,920
GEORGE: Please save me
from the monsters.

424
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:23,960
Please save me from the monsters.

425
00:28:24,920 --> 00:28:26,360
ALEX: George!

426
00:28:29,200 --> 00:28:30,240
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

427
00:28:40,920 --> 00:28:43,400
Why aren't there any lights?
I miss lights.

428
00:28:43,480 --> 00:28:44,800
You don't really miss things
till they're gone, do you?

429
00:28:44,880 --> 00:28:46,000
It's like what my Nan used to say,

430
00:28:46,080 --> 00:28:47,840
"You'll never miss the water
till the well runs dry."

431
00:28:47,920 --> 00:28:49,920
-Rory.
-Except lights, not...

432
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:52,280
Not water. Lights are great,
aren't they?

433
00:28:52,360 --> 00:28:54,600
I mean, if this place was all lit up,
we wouldn't be worried at all.

434
00:28:54,680 --> 00:28:56,840
Rory! Panicking a bit.

435
00:28:57,760 --> 00:28:59,040
-Yeah, yeah, sorry.
-Yeah.

436
00:28:59,120 --> 00:29:01,280
-(DOOR OPENS)
-Help me! Please!

437
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:03,960
Keep them away from me. Keep them away.

438
00:29:04,840 --> 00:29:06,320
(CHILD LAUGHING)

439
00:29:06,400 --> 00:29:07,880
(PURCELL SCREAMING)

440
00:29:08,200 --> 00:29:13,720
# Tick-tock goes the clock

441
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:19,080
# And dolls can shine with fear

442
00:29:20,320 --> 00:29:25,560
-(DOLL GIGGLING)
-# Tick-tock until the day... #

443
00:29:27,760 --> 00:29:30,400
I take it all back. Panic now.

444
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:31,960
(SCREAMING)

445
00:29:32,040 --> 00:29:34,040
DOLL: Don't run away.

446
00:29:34,120 --> 00:29:35,840
(GIGGLING) We want to play.

447
00:29:38,120 --> 00:29:39,520
(GIGGLING)

448
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:07,520
George! George, don't do this.
We want to help you, George!

449
00:30:07,600 --> 00:30:09,440
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

450
00:30:16,880 --> 00:30:19,480
We went... We went into the cupboard.

451
00:30:21,040 --> 00:30:22,760
We went into the cupboard.

452
00:30:24,200 --> 00:30:26,160
How can it be bigger in here?

453
00:30:26,240 --> 00:30:28,840
More common than you'd think, actually.
You okay?

454
00:30:30,080 --> 00:30:31,680
-Where are we?
-Obvious, isn't it?

455
00:30:31,760 --> 00:30:32,760
-No!
-Doll's house.

456
00:30:32,840 --> 00:30:34,600
We're inside the dolls house.

457
00:30:34,680 --> 00:30:36,800
-The dolls house?
-Yeah, in the cupboard, in your flat.

458
00:30:36,880 --> 00:30:38,080
-The dolls house.
-No, look.

459
00:30:38,160 --> 00:30:40,040
-Slow down, would you?
-Look, wooden chicken.

460
00:30:40,120 --> 00:30:42,200
Cups, saucers, plates, knives,
forks, fruit.

461
00:30:42,280 --> 00:30:43,800
The chicken's wood, so...

462
00:30:44,480 --> 00:30:45,840
we're either inside the dolls house

463
00:30:45,920 --> 00:30:48,200
or this is refuge for dirty
posh people who eat wooden food.

464
00:30:48,280 --> 00:30:51,280
Or termites. Giant termites
trying to get on the property ladder.

465
00:30:51,360 --> 00:30:54,320
No. That's possible. Is that possible?

466
00:31:00,520 --> 00:31:02,600
Look, will you stop?

467
00:31:03,680 --> 00:31:05,640
What is he? What is George?

468
00:31:05,720 --> 00:31:08,480
And how could I forget that
Claire can't have kids, how?

469
00:31:08,560 --> 00:31:09,720
Perception filter.

470
00:31:09,800 --> 00:31:11,880
Some kind of hugely
powerful perception filter

471
00:31:11,960 --> 00:31:14,400
convinced you and Claire, everyone,
made you change your memories.

472
00:31:14,480 --> 00:31:16,840
Now, what could do that?

473
00:31:18,360 --> 00:31:19,720
Just a mirror.

474
00:31:20,080 --> 00:31:21,200
(CREAKING)

475
00:31:25,280 --> 00:31:26,520
(DOLL LAUGHING)

476
00:31:26,600 --> 00:31:27,880
(BANGING ON DOOR)

477
00:31:28,960 --> 00:31:30,080
(GRUNTS)

478
00:31:30,760 --> 00:31:31,920
Lock it!

479
00:31:32,480 --> 00:31:34,000
-There isn't a lock.
-(GROANS)

480
00:31:34,080 --> 00:31:35,080
(GRUNTS)

481
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:37,400
No, no, no, no!

482
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:39,760
-(DOLL LAUGHING)
-AMY: Come on!

483
00:31:39,840 --> 00:31:41,000
(GRUNTS)

484
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:46,560
Move, move, move.

485
00:31:51,520 --> 00:31:53,880
So, Claire can't have kids
and something responded to that.

486
00:31:53,960 --> 00:31:55,760
Responded to that need.
What could do that?

487
00:31:56,560 --> 00:32:00,440
I thought you were the expert, fighting
monsters all day long. You tell me.

488
00:32:00,520 --> 00:32:02,400
Oi, listen, mush, old eyes.

489
00:32:02,480 --> 00:32:04,560
Remember? I've been around the block
a few times. More than a few.

490
00:32:04,640 --> 00:32:06,120
-They've knocked down the blocks...
-(LIFT DINGS)

491
00:32:06,200 --> 00:32:07,880
...I've been round
and rebuilt them as bigger blocks.

492
00:32:07,960 --> 00:32:09,240
-Super blocks.
-(WHIRRING)

493
00:32:09,320 --> 00:32:11,360
I've been round them as well.
I can't remember everything.

494
00:32:11,440 --> 00:32:13,000
-Doctor.
-It's like trying to remember the name

495
00:32:13,080 --> 00:32:14,560
of someone you met at a party
when you were two.

496
00:32:14,640 --> 00:32:15,680
Doctor, the lift.

497
00:32:15,760 --> 00:32:17,440
I can't just plump for Brian,
like I normally do.

498
00:32:17,520 --> 00:32:19,240
-Doctor, listen.
-Shh, what's that?

499
00:32:19,320 --> 00:32:22,560
It's the Lift.
It's the sound that the lift makes.

500
00:32:22,640 --> 00:32:24,360
George is scared stiff of it.

501
00:32:25,120 --> 00:32:26,560
(LIFT STOPS)

502
00:32:26,640 --> 00:32:28,280
(ZAPPING)

503
00:32:28,720 --> 00:32:30,400
(LIFT DINGS)

504
00:32:47,400 --> 00:32:50,000
We can't stay in here.
We've got to get out!

505
00:32:50,080 --> 00:32:51,840
Uh, how?

506
00:32:51,920 --> 00:32:55,200
Take control, Rory.
Take control of the only thing we can.

507
00:32:56,160 --> 00:32:57,520
Letting them in.

508
00:32:57,600 --> 00:32:59,040
-Letting them in?
-Surprise them.

509
00:32:59,600 --> 00:33:03,400
We open the door and we push past them.
Kick them, punch them, anything, okay?

510
00:33:03,480 --> 00:33:05,080
DOLL: Time to play!

511
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:07,160
-Okay.
-Okay.

512
00:33:07,320 --> 00:33:10,160
# Tick-tock goes the clock #

513
00:33:10,640 --> 00:33:12,320
(BANGING ON DOOR)

514
00:33:13,160 --> 00:33:15,160
Go on!

515
00:33:15,240 --> 00:33:18,760
-RORY: Amy, come on.
-# Tick-tock until the day... #

516
00:33:18,840 --> 00:33:21,800
-AMY: Rory, Rory!
-Amy! Get off.

517
00:33:22,240 --> 00:33:23,680
(AMY SCREAMING)

518
00:33:23,760 --> 00:33:27,560
-(CREAKING)
-# Tick-tock goes the clock

519
00:33:27,640 --> 00:33:31,320
# And all the years they cry

520
00:33:31,400 --> 00:33:34,680
# Tick-tock and all too soon

521
00:33:34,760 --> 00:33:37,440
# You and I must die #

522
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:39,120
(DOLL GIGGLING)

523
00:33:44,040 --> 00:33:45,400
Five times.

524
00:33:46,360 --> 00:33:48,800
The lights. It's happening five times.

525
00:33:49,520 --> 00:33:50,840
It's like one of George's habits.

526
00:33:50,920 --> 00:33:53,240
We have to switch the lights
on and off five times.

527
00:33:53,320 --> 00:33:55,400
-Now you're getting it.
-What do you mean?

528
00:33:55,480 --> 00:33:58,120
What do you tell George to do, Alex,
with everything that scares him?

529
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:00,800
Well, put it in the...cupboard.

530
00:34:00,880 --> 00:34:02,720
Exactly. And George isn't
just an ordinary little boy,

531
00:34:02,800 --> 00:34:06,240
we know that now.
So, anything scary he puts in here.

532
00:34:06,320 --> 00:34:10,120
Scary toys, like the dolls house.
Scary noises, like the Lift.

533
00:34:10,720 --> 00:34:12,520
Even his own rituals
have become part of it.

534
00:34:12,600 --> 00:34:15,480
A psychic repository for all his fears.

535
00:34:15,560 --> 00:34:16,840
But what is he?

536
00:34:16,920 --> 00:34:18,520
(DOLL LAUGHING)

537
00:34:25,360 --> 00:34:26,560
Oh, my God.

538
00:34:26,640 --> 00:34:27,640
(DOLL LAUGHING)

539
00:34:28,960 --> 00:34:30,040
(ALEX EXCLAIMS)

540
00:34:31,960 --> 00:34:34,320
-A gun? You've got a gun?
-It's not a gun.

541
00:34:34,560 --> 00:34:35,600
What?

542
00:34:35,680 --> 00:34:38,080
I've got to invent a setting for wood.
It's embarrassing.

543
00:34:38,160 --> 00:34:39,280
(DOLL LAUGHING)

544
00:34:42,120 --> 00:34:43,440
DOCTOR: Run!

545
00:34:43,520 --> 00:34:46,720
DOLL: Don't run away.
We just want to play.

546
00:34:47,600 --> 00:34:50,680
(GEORGE BREATHING HEAVILY)

547
00:34:57,680 --> 00:35:00,520
Massive psychic field,
perfect perception filter and that need,

548
00:35:00,600 --> 00:35:03,120
that need of Claire's to...to...

549
00:35:03,200 --> 00:35:05,080
Stupid Doctor! Ow!

550
00:35:05,160 --> 00:35:07,400
George is a Tenza. Of course he is.

551
00:35:07,480 --> 00:35:09,160
-He's a what?
-A cuckoo.

552
00:35:09,240 --> 00:35:11,800
A cuckoo in the nest.
A Tenza, he's a Tenza.

553
00:35:11,880 --> 00:35:14,240
Millions of them hatch in space
and then, woof!

554
00:35:14,320 --> 00:35:16,000
Off they drift, looking for a nest.

555
00:35:16,080 --> 00:35:18,760
The Tenza young can sense exactly
what their foster parents want

556
00:35:18,840 --> 00:35:20,400
and then they assimilate perfectly.

557
00:35:21,200 --> 00:35:23,600
-George is an alien?
-Yep.

558
00:35:23,680 --> 00:35:25,360
But he's our child!

559
00:35:25,440 --> 00:35:28,000
Of course he is.
The child you always wanted.

560
00:35:28,080 --> 00:35:30,120
He sensed that instinctively
and sought you out.

561
00:35:30,200 --> 00:35:31,920
But something scared him.

562
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:34,360
Started a cycle of fear,
it's all completely instinctive.

563
00:35:34,440 --> 00:35:37,360
Subconscious. George isn't even
aware that he's controlling it.

564
00:35:38,120 --> 00:35:41,600
So, we have to make him aware. George!

565
00:35:42,120 --> 00:35:43,520
(GEORGE BREATHING HEAVILY)

566
00:35:43,600 --> 00:35:47,320
George, you are the only one who can
stop this, but you have to believe.

567
00:35:47,400 --> 00:35:49,080
You have to believe.
You have to know you're safe.

568
00:35:49,160 --> 00:35:50,200
(GEORGE BREATHING HEAVILY)

569
00:35:50,280 --> 00:35:52,040
I can't save you from your monsters,
only you can.

570
00:35:52,120 --> 00:35:53,200
(DOLL GIGGLING)

571
00:35:53,280 --> 00:35:55,120
George, listen to me!

572
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:57,360
George, listen to me!

573
00:35:58,320 --> 00:36:00,440
(DOLL GIGGLING)

574
00:36:00,520 --> 00:36:01,760
Rory!

575
00:36:01,840 --> 00:36:03,080
-Doctor!
-Where's Amy?

576
00:36:03,160 --> 00:36:04,320
(DOLL GIGGLING)

577
00:36:06,080 --> 00:36:07,080
Oh, no.

578
00:36:07,160 --> 00:36:11,080
George! George, you have to face
your fears! You have to face them now.

579
00:36:12,400 --> 00:36:13,440
(DOLLS GIGGLING)

580
00:36:13,520 --> 00:36:14,760
You have to open the cupboard.

581
00:36:15,280 --> 00:36:17,680
We'll all be trapped here forever
in a living death.

582
00:36:17,760 --> 00:36:20,000
George. George, listen to me.

583
00:36:20,680 --> 00:36:22,880
George. George, listen to me!

584
00:36:24,760 --> 00:36:26,080
George!

585
00:36:27,080 --> 00:36:29,800
Please. George, you have to end this.

586
00:36:31,040 --> 00:36:34,000
End this, end this. End it now!

587
00:36:36,160 --> 00:36:37,600
(GIGGLING STOPS)

588
00:36:38,680 --> 00:36:40,560
(MEN PANTING)

589
00:36:45,720 --> 00:36:46,720
George.

590
00:36:47,440 --> 00:36:48,440
George.

591
00:36:49,200 --> 00:36:50,360
You did it.

592
00:36:50,880 --> 00:36:52,040
You did it.

593
00:36:52,640 --> 00:36:54,360
Hey, it's okay, it's all okay now.

594
00:36:54,440 --> 00:36:55,600
Everything's going to be fine.

595
00:36:55,680 --> 00:36:58,120
-(CREAKING)
-# Tick-tock

596
00:36:58,200 --> 00:36:59,320
-No.
-# Goes the clock... #

597
00:36:59,400 --> 00:37:01,760
No, no, no, no!

598
00:37:02,200 --> 00:37:05,160
George, you created this whole world.

599
00:37:05,240 --> 00:37:07,400
This whole thing. You can smash it.

600
00:37:07,800 --> 00:37:09,040
You can destroy it.

601
00:37:10,520 --> 00:37:12,960
Something's holding you back.
Something's holding him back.

602
00:37:13,040 --> 00:37:14,640
Something.

603
00:37:14,720 --> 00:37:16,800
GEORGE: Who are you?
DOCTOR: I'm the Doctor.

604
00:37:16,880 --> 00:37:20,400
A doctor? Have you come to take me away?

605
00:37:20,480 --> 00:37:21,800
That's what it is.
That's what the trigger was.

606
00:37:21,880 --> 00:37:23,880
He thought you were rejecting him.
He thought he wasn't wanted.

607
00:37:23,960 --> 00:37:25,320
That someone was going to come
and take him away.

608
00:37:25,400 --> 00:37:27,720
Well, we... We talked about it.

609
00:37:27,800 --> 00:37:28,960
DOCTOR: Yeah, and he heard you.

610
00:37:29,040 --> 00:37:30,640
Alex, a Tenza's sole function
is to fit in, to be wanted,

611
00:37:30,720 --> 00:37:32,080
and you were rejecting him.

612
00:37:32,160 --> 00:37:34,120
We just couldn't cope. We needed help.

613
00:37:34,200 --> 00:37:36,680
Yes, but George didn't know that.
He thought you were rejecting him.

614
00:37:36,760 --> 00:37:38,040
He still thinks it.

615
00:37:38,120 --> 00:37:39,400
How can we keep him?

616
00:37:39,480 --> 00:37:41,240
-How can we? He's not...
-Not what?

617
00:37:41,320 --> 00:37:42,760
(DOLLS GIGGLING)

618
00:37:42,840 --> 00:37:43,960
He's not...

619
00:37:45,040 --> 00:37:46,200
human.

620
00:37:46,280 --> 00:37:47,440
(DOLLS GIGGLING)

621
00:37:49,800 --> 00:37:51,160
No.

622
00:37:51,240 --> 00:37:52,520
GEORGE: Dad!

623
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:55,960
(DOLLS LAUGHING)

624
00:38:10,760 --> 00:38:14,120
Whatever you are, whatever you do,

625
00:38:14,200 --> 00:38:15,680
you're my son.

626
00:38:16,600 --> 00:38:18,400
And I will never,

627
00:38:18,480 --> 00:38:20,480
ever, send you away.

628
00:38:21,560 --> 00:38:23,200
Come on, George.

629
00:38:24,320 --> 00:38:25,920
Oh, my little boy.

630
00:38:27,200 --> 00:38:28,600
GEORGE: Dad.

631
00:38:33,960 --> 00:38:35,440
My little boy.

632
00:38:36,320 --> 00:38:37,680
Dad.

633
00:38:47,880 --> 00:38:49,920
(GRUNTING)

634
00:38:53,680 --> 00:38:55,000
Oh, dear.

635
00:38:57,520 --> 00:38:59,480
Must be them tablets.

636
00:39:00,560 --> 00:39:01,720
Oh.

637
00:39:02,520 --> 00:39:03,720
Oh, dear.

638
00:39:03,800 --> 00:39:04,960
(LIFT DINGS)

639
00:39:11,320 --> 00:39:12,760
-Was 1...?
-Yeah.

640
00:39:30,400 --> 00:39:32,320
ALEX: All right, stay still.

641
00:39:32,400 --> 00:39:33,520
Or I'll come and get you.

642
00:39:33,600 --> 00:39:35,080
(DOOR OPENS)

643
00:39:35,160 --> 00:39:36,400
Hi.

644
00:39:36,480 --> 00:39:37,920
(GEORGE LAUGHING)

645
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:39,200
(GRUNTS)

646
00:39:42,160 --> 00:39:43,800
(GEORGE LAUGHS)

647
00:39:43,880 --> 00:39:46,280
Hello! You're Claire, I expect.

648
00:39:46,360 --> 00:39:47,360
Claire.

649
00:39:48,560 --> 00:39:49,720
How do you feel about kippers?

650
00:39:50,040 --> 00:39:51,040
Uh...

651
00:39:51,120 --> 00:39:52,760
They sent someone, about George.

652
00:39:53,440 --> 00:39:55,640
-It's all sorted.
-Yeah, we had a great time, didn't we?

653
00:39:55,720 --> 00:39:57,480
-Yeah.
-See? He's fine.

654
00:39:59,200 --> 00:40:00,280
What, just like that?

655
00:40:00,760 --> 00:40:01,960
Yes.

656
00:40:03,040 --> 00:40:04,240
Trust me.

657
00:40:14,480 --> 00:40:16,960
-Doctor, wait.
-Sorry, yes, bye.

658
00:40:17,040 --> 00:40:18,800
No, no, you can't just... I mean...

659
00:40:18,880 --> 00:40:21,400
It's sorted, you sorted it.
Good man, Alex. Proud of you.

660
00:40:21,480 --> 00:40:22,520
What, that's it?

661
00:40:22,600 --> 00:40:24,560
Well, apart from making sure
he eats his greens

662
00:40:24,640 --> 00:40:25,920
and getting him into a good school, yes.

663
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:27,400
Yeah, but is he going to...

664
00:40:27,480 --> 00:40:30,240
I don't know, sprout another head
or three eyes or something?

665
00:40:30,320 --> 00:40:31,920
He's one of the Tenza, remember.

666
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:33,920
He'll adapt perfectly now. Eh!

667
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:35,520
Be whatever you want him to be.

668
00:40:41,240 --> 00:40:45,400
Might pop back around puberty, mind you.
Always a funny time.

669
00:40:48,520 --> 00:40:50,160
CLAIRE: Kippers are getting cold.

670
00:40:53,880 --> 00:40:56,120
Come on, you two. Things to do.

671
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:58,160
People to see,
whole civilizations to save.

672
00:40:58,240 --> 00:41:00,800
-You feeling okay?
-Um, I think so.

673
00:41:00,880 --> 00:41:02,760
Well, it's good to be all back
together again.

674
00:41:02,840 --> 00:41:04,480
In the flesh.

675
00:41:05,600 --> 00:41:06,760
Come on.

676
00:41:07,080 --> 00:41:10,040
Now, did someone mention something
about planets and history and stuff?

677
00:41:10,120 --> 00:41:11,880
-RORY: Yeah.
-Where do you want to go?

678
00:41:11,960 --> 00:41:13,760
-Um...
-Mind's gone blank.

679
00:41:13,840 --> 00:41:15,440
Well, I have just been turned
into a wooden dolly.

680
00:41:15,520 --> 00:41:16,760
Excuses, excuses.

681
00:41:16,840 --> 00:41:19,520
It's tough, though.
It's like being given three wishes.

682
00:41:19,600 --> 00:41:20,800
The whole universe.

683
00:41:20,880 --> 00:41:22,880
The universe is... Ooh!

684
00:41:22,960 --> 00:41:25,680
-Three wishes. Ali Baba. How about that?
-#Tick-tock goes the clock

685
00:41:25,760 --> 00:41:30,000
# The cradle man, he rocked her #

686
00:41:30,080 --> 00:41:33,520
# Tick-tock goes the clock

687
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:37,200
# Even for the Doctor #

688
00:41:40,320 --> 00:41:41,360
Where am I?

689
00:41:41,440 --> 00:41:42,920
DOCTOR: You're in a faster time stream.

690
00:41:43,120 --> 00:41:44,880
-RORY: Amy.
-You didn't save me.

691
00:41:45,200 --> 00:41:48,080
RORY: So, I have to choose,
which wife do I want?

692
00:41:48,560 --> 00:41:49,600
Which one's Amy 1?

693
00:41:49,680 --> 00:41:51,120
AMY: As they touch you, you go to sleep.

694
00:41:51,440 --> 00:41:52,440
(ZAPPING)

695
00:41:57,600 --> 00:41:59,720
(SHOUTING)

